        "atomic_number":57,
        "name":"Lanthanum",
        "symbol":"La",
        "LanthanideandActinide":"Lanthanide",
        "electronic_configuration":"[Xe] 5d 6s2",
        "electron_gain_enthalpy":-45.34795,
        "Analysis":"The lanthanides display an irregular electron gain enthalpy trend, shaped by the gradual filling of the 4f orbitals and the effects of lanthanide contraction. From lanthanum (La) to praseodymium (Pr), the electron gain enthalpy becomes more negative as the effective nuclear charge increases due to the poor shielding by the 4f electrons.\n\nThe trend is interrupted by especially stable electronic configurations. Europium (Eu) has a less negative electron gain enthalpy because its half-filled 4f\u2077 configuration resists the addition of an electron. Thulium (Tm) becomes more favorable again, as gaining an electron completes the highly stable 4f\u00b9\u2074 configuration.\n\nYtterbium (Yb) is the biggest surprise. With its already filled 4f\u00b9\u2074 subshell, an extra electron must enter the higher-energy 5d orbital, giving it a slightly positive electron gain enthalpy. Lutetium (Lu) then returns to a moderately negative value as the incoming electron occupies the 5d subshell, providing only limited stabilization.",
        "jmol_color":"#70d4ff"
    },
