    {
        "atomic_number":89,
        "name":"Actinium",
        "symbol":"Ac",
        "LanthanideandActinide":"Actinide",
        "electronic_configuration":"[Rn] 6d 7s2",
        "electron_gain_enthalpy":-33.76975,
        "Analysis":"The actinides remain one of the least explored regions of the periodic table. Reliable electron gain enthalpy data are available only for actinium (Ac), while values for the remaining actinides are largely unknown because these elements are highly radioactive and extremely difficult to study.\n\nTheoretical predictions suggest an irregular trend, shaped by the progressive filling of the 5f orbitals, electron pairing, and actinide contraction. As the effective nuclear charge increases across the series, the attraction for an incoming electron generally becomes stronger.\n\nHowever, electronic configuration introduces important exceptions. The half-filled 5f\u2077 configuration of americium and the filled 5f\u00b9\u2074 configuration of nobelium are especially stable, making electron gain less favorable.\n\nIn the heavier actinides, strong relativistic effects further reshape the 5f, 6d, and 7s orbitals, producing deviations from simple periodic trends and making the electron gain behavior of these elements one of the most intriguing challenges in modern chemistry.",
        "jmol_color":"#70abfa"
    },
